    • describeConstable

      public Optional<? extends ConstantDesc> describeConstable()
      Returns an Optional housing a ConstantDesc that represents this Types.

      This method never returns null.

      The default implementation of this method relies on the presence of a public constructor that accepts a single Domain-typed argument.

      The Optional returned by an invocation of this method may be, and often will be, empty.

    • equals

      public boolean equals(Object other)
      Returns true if and only if the supplied Object is equal to this Types.

      The supplied Object is considered to be equal to this Types if and only if its class is that of this Types, and if the return value of an invocation of this Types' domain() method is equal to the Domain returned by an invocation of the other Types' domain() method.

    • supertypes

      public final SupertypeList supertypes(TypeMirror t)
      Returns a non-null SupertypeList of the supertypes of the supplied TypeMirror.

      No element in the returned List will be null.

      The supplied TypeMirror will be the first element in the returned SupertypeList. (The supertype relation is reflexive.)

      No two elements in the list will be equal or the same type. (The List is an ordered set.)

      This method returns determinate values.

      The elements of the returned List will be in the following (partial) order:

      1. The supplied TypeMirror precedes any other elements.
      2. Subtypes precede supertypes.
      3. Non-interface types precede interface types.
      Parameters:
      t - a TypeMirror; must not be null
      Returns:
      a non-null SupertypeList of the supertypes of the supplied TypeMirror
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if t is null
      See Also:
      • supertypes(TypeMirror, Predicate)
      • Domain.directSupertypes(TypeMirror)
      External Specifications
      • Java Language Specification, section 4.10
      • Java Language Specification, section 4.10.2

    • supertypes

      public final SupertypeList supertypes(TypeMirror t, Predicate<? super TypeMirror> p)
      Returns a non-null SupertypeList of the supertypes of the supplied TypeMirror, filtered using the supplied Predicate.

      No element in the returned SupertypeList will be null.

      Unless the supplied Predicate prevents it, the supplied TypeMirror will be the first element in the returned SupertypeList. (The supertype relation is reflexive.)

      No two elements in the list will be equal or the same type. (The SupertypeList is an ordered set.)

      This method returns determinate values.

      The elements of the returned SupertypeList will be in the following (partial) order:

      1. Subtypes precede supertypes.
      2. Non-interface types precede interface types.
      Parameters:
      t - a TypeMirror; must not be null
      p - a Predicate; must not be null
      Returns:
      a non-null SupertypeList of the supertypes of the supplied TypeMirror, filtered using the supplied Predicate
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if either t or p is null
      See Also:
      • Domain.directSupertypes(TypeMirror)
      External Specifications
      • Java Language Specification, section 4.10
      • Java Language Specification, section 4.10.2

    • erasedName

      public static final String erasedName(TypeMirror t)
      Returns the erased name of the supplied TypeMirror.

      Erased name is not a term defined or used by the Java Language Specification. Its definition and contract follow.

      This method is primarily for use in calculating tiebreaking values for type-related comparison operations where type erasure can be in effect. It is also useful in testing scenarios. Most users will never call this method.

      The erased name of a declared type of any kind is the erased name of its declaring Element.

      The erased name of an element is its qualified name, if it has one, or its simple name if it does not.

      The erased name of the boolean primitive type is boolean.

      The erased name of the byte primitive type is byte.

      The erased name of the char primitive type is char.

      The erased name of the double primitive type is double.

      The erased name of the float primitive type is float.

      The erased name of the int primitive type is int.

      The erased name of the long primitive type is long.

      The erased name of the short primitive type is short.

      The erased name of the void type is void.

      The erased name of a type variable is the erased name of its declaring TypeParameterElement.

      The erased name of an intersection type is the String formed by joining the erased names of its bounds with "&".

      The erased name of an array type is the String formed by concatenating the erased name of its component type with "[]".

      The erased name of any other TypeMirror is the return value of an invocation of its toString() method.

      Parameters:
      t - a TypeMirror; must not be null
      Returns:
      the erased name of the supplied TypeMirror; never null
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if t is null
